values:
It has been a long time coming, but I find it more difficult to accept my parents views of how things should be as right. I know that any woman out there, in particular women who are anything American first generation immigrant, or first born in America find it difficult to identify with their cultural background completely not influenced by where they live now, in America. The pressures of women having to abide by their cultural and familial standards in a country where freedom and equality are preached to them everyday is not only frustraiting, but also very difficult and emotionally tiring. Families expect their young women to follow all the rules they instil, while going through schools young women learn that they can be treated equally to all of their peers, including the males, and the social stigma of male to female roles is not as much in place as it is in other cultures and countries.&nbsp;

That being said it is difficult to expect female anything Americans, as all women are encompassed in this from other cultural backgrounds, to follow exactly what their families want them to. Which brings me back to my original point, I cannot stand how no matter how hard I try, and I&#39;m not sure how many of you out there feel the same, I cannot please anyone, finding that my cultural background as a first generation immigrant women raised in both my home country and here is not satisfied with my attempts to balance both. My family expects me to be the perfect young woman, who follows their rules and how they want me brought up (a Catholic abiding familial regulations angel). Americans are surprised that I&#39;m not their ideal of the busy working modern business woman who finds comfort in a busy downtown life style with not enough time for sleep. I just want to point out one thing, why can anyone not accept that I would rather be a me I formed as a 22 year old, college graduate, that loves to balance both worlds. Who I still very much a modern woman, Pagan, Liberal, unaffiliated with any political movements, school teacher, who loves to go out on certain weekends, stay in on others, and simply enjoys being who she is without anyone trying to change her. I am very comfortable in my own skin, so why can no one else in both worlds appreciate that? Strictly speaking of society and families here.&nbsp;

Anything Ameican women have a certain standard they must adhere to on both sides and cannot begin to know which one is better. Do you honor familial wishes though you do not agree? Or do you honor the wishes of society to better fit in? Do you stay true to yourself and fight constantly with both sides and grow tired of pointless arguments? Do you give in and lose yourself to simply be left alone and please both sides in different situations? Sadly there is no answer. Each woman must find her own way, but simply until culutral backgrounds and the current place of inhabitance see the stress and difficulties anything American women have to survive each day, there will never be the calm peace each side wishes for their daughters, mothers, &nbsp;sisters, and friends.&nbsp;
